# Translations

This document defines how to use translations in the Glint admin application. Follow these patterns to ensure consistent translation implementation across server and client components.

## Core principles

- Use server-side translations for server components
- Use client-side translations for client components
- Always use the `t()` function for user-facing text in components
- Use `/* i18n */` comments for translatable strings outside components
- Pass English text as the argument to `t()` or after `/* i18n */`
- Never hardcode translated text

## Server components

Server components must use the async `getServerI18n` function.

### Import pattern

```typescript
import {getServerI18n} from '@/lib/i18n-server';
```

### Usage pattern

```typescript
const Page: React.FC<Props> = async ({params}) => {
    const {locale, screenerId} = await params;
    const {t} = await getServerI18n(locale);

    return (
        <div>
            <h1>{t('Page title')}</h1>
            <p>{t('Page description')}</p>
        </div>
    );
};
```

### Key requirements

- Extract `locale` from params
- Await both `params` and `getServerI18n(locale)`
- Destructure `{t}` from the result
- Use `t()` for all user-facing text

### Example

```typescript
import {getServerI18n} from '@/lib/i18n-server';

interface Props {
    params: Promise<{locale: Locale; screenerId: string}>;
}

const Page: React.FC<Props> = async ({params}) => {
    const {locale, screenerId} = await params;
    const {t} = await getServerI18n(locale);

    return (
        <Container>
            <SectionHeader title={t('Screener details')} />
        </Container>
    );
};
```

## Client components

Client components must use the synchronous `useI18n` hook.

### Import pattern

```typescript
import {useI18n} from '@/hooks/use-i18n';
```

### Usage pattern

```typescript
'use client';

const Component: React.FC = () => {
    const {t} = useI18n();

    return (
        <div>
            <button>{t('Click me')}</button>
            <span>{t('Status')}</span>
        </div>
    );
};
```

### Key requirements

- Add `'use client'` directive at the top of the file
- Call `useI18n()` within the component
- Destructure `{t}` from the result
- Use `t()` for all user-facing text

### Example

```typescript
'use client';

import Button from '@glint/ui/button';
import {useI18n} from '@/hooks/use-i18n';

const SurveyNavbar: React.FC<Props> = ({surveyId}) => {
    const {t} = useI18n();

    return (
        <nav>
            <Button>{t('Overview')}</Button>
            <Button>{t('Settings')}</Button>
            <Button>{t('Questions')}</Button>
        </nav>
    );
};
```

## Non-component code

For strings outside React components (utilities, constants, schemas), use the `/* i18n */` comment to mark translatable strings.

### When to use `/* i18n */` comments

Use this pattern for:

- Utility functions that return user-facing text
- Constant objects with translatable strings
- Schema error messages
- Configuration objects with labels
- Any non-component code with user-facing strings

### Usage pattern

Add `/* i18n */` comment before any string that needs translation:

```typescript
// utility function
export function getStatusLabel(status: string): string {
    switch (status) {
        case 'active':
            return /* i18n */ 'Active';
        case 'inactive':
            return /* i18n */ 'Inactive';
        default:
            return /* i18n */ 'Unknown';
    }
}

// constant object
export const QUESTION_TYPES = {
    text: /* i18n */ 'Text',
    number: /* i18n */ 'Number',
    select: /* i18n */ 'Selection',
} as const;

// schema error messages
export const surveySchema = z.object({
    title: z.string().min(1, /* i18n */ 'Title is required'),
    description: z.string().min(10, /* i18n */ 'Description must be at least 10 characters'),
});
```

### Key requirements

- Place `/* i18n */` immediately before the string literal
- Use English text as the string value
- The translation system will extract these strings automatically
- **Only use `/* i18n */` in non-component code** - never in React components
- **Never combine `/* i18n */` with `t()`** - they are mutually exclusive patterns
- These strings will be translated at runtime when used in components

### Example with utility function

```typescript
// utilities/format.ts
export function formatQuestionType(type: string): string {
    const labels: Record<string, string> = {
        text: /* i18n */ 'Text input',
        number: /* i18n */ 'Number input',
        select_one: /* i18n */ 'Single choice',
        select_multiple: /* i18n */ 'Multiple choice',
        date: /* i18n */ 'Date picker',
    };
    return labels[type] || /* i18n */ 'Unknown type';
}
```

### Example with constants

```typescript
// constants/statuses.ts
export const SURVEY_STATUSES = {
    draft: {
        label: /* i18n */ 'Draft',
        color: 'gray',
    },
    active: {
        label: /* i18n */ 'Active',
        color: 'green',
    },
    archived: {
        label: /* i18n */ 'Archived',
        color: 'red',
    },
} as const;
```

### Example with validation schemas

```typescript
// schemas/campaign.ts
import {z} from 'zod';

export const campaignSchema = z.object({
    name: z.string().min(1, /* i18n */ 'Campaign name is required'),
    startDate: z.date({
        required_error: /* i18n */ 'Start date is required',
        invalid_type_error: /* i18n */ 'Invalid date format',
    }),
    budget: z.number().positive(/* i18n */ 'Budget must be positive'),
});
```

### Using marked strings in components

The marked strings can be used in components by passing them through `t()`:

```typescript
'use client';

import {useI18n} from '@/hooks/use-i18n';
import {getStatusLabel} from '@/utils/format';

const StatusDisplay: React.FC<{status: string}> = ({status}) => {
    const {t} = useI18n();
    const label = getStatusLabel(status);
    
    return <span>{t(label)}</span>;
};
```

### Do not mix patterns

```typescript
// ❌ Incorrect - never use /* i18n */ with t()
const {t} = useI18n();
return <button>{t(/* i18n */ 'Click me')}</button>;

// ✅ Correct - use t() only in components
const {t} = useI18n();
return <button>{t('Click me')}</button>;

// ❌ Incorrect - never use /* i18n */ with t()
const message = t(/* i18n */ 'Hello world');

// ✅ Correct - use t() only
const message = t('Hello world');
```

### Important notes

- The `/* i18n */` comment is for marking strings, not translating them
- Actual translation happens when the string is passed to `t()` in a component
- This pattern helps the translation system extract all translatable strings
- **Never add `/* i18n */` comments to strings already wrapped in `t()`** - choose one or the other
- Use `t()` in components, use `/* i18n */` in non-component code

## Common patterns

### Translation keys

Pass English text as the translation key:

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
t('User settings')
t('Save changes')
t('Delete survey')

// ❌ Incorrect - do not use key-based translations
t('user.settings')
t('actions.save')
t('survey.delete')
```

### Dynamic text

For text with dynamic values, use template literals outside the translation:

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
const message = `${t('Responses')}: ${count}`;
const title = `${survey.title} - ${t('Settings')}`;

// ❌ Incorrect - do not interpolate inside t()
const message = t(`Responses: ${count}`);
```

### Conditional text

Keep translation calls separate for different conditions:

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
const label = isActive ? t('Active') : t('Inactive');
const status = hasLaunched ? t('Live') : t('Draft');

// ❌ Incorrect - translate the entire condition
const label = t(isActive ? 'Active' : 'Inactive');
```

## Common mistakes

### Using server translations in client components

```typescript
// ❌ Incorrect - getServerI18n cannot be used in client components
'use client';

const Component = async () => {
    const {t} = await getServerI18n('en');
    return <div>{t('Text')}</div>;
};
```

### Using client translations in server components

```typescript
// ❌ Incorrect - useI18n is a hook and cannot be used in server components
const Page = async () => {
    const {t} = useI18n();
    return <div>{t('Text')}</div>;
};
```

### Not awaiting server translations

```typescript
// ❌ Incorrect - must await getServerI18n
const Page = async ({params}) => {
    const {locale} = await params;
    const {t} = getServerI18n(locale); // Missing await
    return <div>{t('Text')}</div>;
};
```

### Forgetting 'use client' directive

```typescript
// ❌ Incorrect - missing 'use client' directive
import {useI18n} from '@/hooks/use-i18n';

const Component = () => {
    const {t} = useI18n(); // Will fail without 'use client'
    return <div>{t('Text')}</div>;
};
```

## Type safety

Both translation functions accept strings and provide type-safe autocomplete for existing translations. The translation system uses English text as keys, so you can type any English phrase and it will be automatically added to the translation system.

## Verification checklist

Before completing any translation implementation, verify:

1. **Component type**: Is this a server or client component, or non-component code?
2. **Correct import**: Using `getServerI18n` for server, `useI18n` for client
3. **Async handling**: Server translations are awaited
4. **Client directive**: Client components have `'use client'` directive
5. **English text**: All user-facing text uses `t()` with English strings or `/* i18n */` comments
6. **Locale parameter**: Server components extract locale from params
7. **Non-component strings**: All translatable strings outside components have `/* i18n */` comments

## Migration guide

### Converting hardcoded text to translations

```typescript
// Before
<button>Save Changes</button>

// After (client component)
const {t} = useI18n();
<button>{t('Save changes')}</button>

// After (server component)
const {t} = await getServerI18n(locale);
<button>{t('Save changes')}</button>
```

### Converting server component to use translations

```typescript
// Before
const Page = async ({params}) => {
    return <h1>Survey Details</h1>;
};

// After
import {getServerI18n} from '@/lib/i18n-server';

const Page = async ({params}) => {
    const {locale} = await params;
    const {t} = await getServerI18n(locale);
    return <h1>{t('Survey details')}</h1>;
};
```

### Converting client component to use translations

```typescript
// Before
const Component = () => {
    return <button>Click Me</button>;
};

// After
'use client';

import {useI18n} from '@/hooks/use-i18n';

const Component = () => {
    const {t} = useI18n();
    return <button>{t('Click me')}</button>;
};
```

### Converting non-component code to use translations

```typescript
// Before
export const STATUS_LABELS = {
    active: 'Active',
    inactive: 'Inactive',
    pending: 'Pending',
};

// After
export const STATUS_LABELS = {
    active: /* i18n */ 'Active',
    inactive: /* i18n */ 'Inactive',
    pending: /* i18n */ 'Pending',
};
```

```typescript
// Before
export function validateSurvey(data: unknown) {
    return z.object({
        title: z.string().min(1, 'Title is required'),
    }).parse(data);
}

// After
export function validateSurvey(data: unknown) {
    return z.object({
        title: z.string().min(1, /* i18n */ 'Title is required'),
    }).parse(data);
}
```
